data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new **span conversion rules** that change overload resolution. Your `array.Contains(num)` now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

The `MemoryExtensions` method **cannot be represented in an expression tree**, so it throws at runtime (typically `InvalidOperationException` or `NotSupportedException`).

## How to fix

Force the call to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by making the receiver an `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these prevent the compiler from selecting the span overload.
